 <caption>
  <p>Differentiating features of Zika, Dengue, and Chikungunya</p>
 </caption>
 <table frame="hsides" rules="groups">
  <thead>
   <tr>
    <th align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Features</th>
    <th align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Dengue</th>
    <th align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Zika</th>
    <th align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Chikungunya</th>
   </tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
   <tr>
    <td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Incubation period</td>
    <td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">3-14 days</td>
    <td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">3-12 days</td>
    <td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">1-12 days</td>
   </tr>
   <tr>
    <td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Etiology</td>
    <td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">RNA virus belongs to the genus 
     <italic>Flavivirus</italic> of family 
     <italic>Flaviviridae</italic>. (4 different serological types exists - DENV 1, 2, 3 and 4) Mostly, Infection with one serotype Leads to lifelong immunity against the same type. However, occasionally, exposure of the individual to a second type of dengue virus Leads to a very severe form of illness (dengue shock syndrome and dengue hemorrhagic fever)
    </td>
    <td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">RNA virus belongs to the genus 
     <italic>Flavivirus</italic>of family 
     <italic>Flaviviridae</italic>. Lifelong immunity after infection with one type has not been reported in Zika virus infections
    </td>
    <td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">RNA virus of genus 
     <italic>Alphavirus</italic>of the family 
     <italic>Togaviridae</italic>
    </td>
   </tr>
   <tr>
    <td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Fever (duration)</td>
    <td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Higher (≥40°)
     <break/>+++
     <break/>Lasts for 4-7 days
    </td>
    <td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Lower (≤38.5)
     <break/>++
     <break/>Lasts for 1-2 days
    </td>
    <td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">High fever++Lasts for 2-3 days</td>
   </tr>
   <tr>
    <td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Rash (maculopapular exanthema)</td>
    <td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Moderately elevated
     <break/>+
    </td>
